The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired this time by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company created a robot that, by imitating the theft of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Centre have made this little robot in collaboration with the Centre for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Trademark Management, the BR23C represents the rise of the Nissan security shield.
This robot will allow the brand's vehicles to prevent collisions.
During flight, each bee creates its own personal space with an oval shape that looks much like the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the bee's eyes, able to see in an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers have developed what is known as a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles over a distance of two metres and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"When it detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by bifurcating its wheels by 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape manoeuvre is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Transportation Laboratory and the main engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted upwards or downwards, nor diagonally; it can move only in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, but also an acceleration and deceleration function, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
" Each second this device must only process information and act according to that data.
It does not need to keep the information or intuitive logics of prior maneuvers, which is why it can operate continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes."
This is the first car to develop new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that will be introduced into standard cars in a decade after Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device to a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
