His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces Wall Street's biggest names to take a much more cautious attitude than before.
The terms presented on Monday also show that the agreement has been modified in recent days: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to Japanese for about 8.5 billion dollars.
"A week ago," Toshihide Mizuno, the executive director of MUFG, told Tokyo, "we thought the stake would be entirely composed of ordinary shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to minimize risks and cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of the profit per share.
The agreement previews that MUFG will be able to convert in one year half of its preferential securities into common shares if the latter exchange more than 50% above the conversion price, i.e. at about 47 dollars, during a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital provided by MUFG will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
However, a spokesperson for the group refused to provide details on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
After MUFG's investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to have a Tier One solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in the sector.
Morgan said he had "clearly" lightened his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been challenging for the group, which has seen its stock exchange price melt in half while the cost of insurance against default risk on its debt is flying away.
This cost fluctuated on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other "survivor" of Wall Street's major investment banks after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the takeover of Merrill Lynch, announced that it had raised $15 billion, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett's group.
Rafael Correa in Quito this Monday.
Refounding the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, like his counterparts and friends, he was the third to put to the vote a draft new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" obtained 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% were white votes.
In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to obtain half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the exit of the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a large victory of the "yes", between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed in the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The "Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly," he assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the headquarters of Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometres south-west of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by her Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place in a calm atmosphere according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), focused on a 444-point text consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the President.
The draft Constitution enshrines the power of the State over the economy, reserving to it the "planning of the development" of a country living essentially from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and foreign currency sent by its emigrants.
Ported by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants enhanced powers to the Head of State, who can carry out up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that it will use this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services which the President has begun to establish in that country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US drug operations.
The 19 hostages were released in Chad
An Egyptian commando attacked the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive for ten days in the desert were brought back this Monday afternoon safe and sound in the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they had been released by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in good shape, the hostages arrived at about 3.30 p.m. aboard a special plane at al-Maza military base, next to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, aboard helicopters to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for examination.
They are in "good health", and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers," said Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
Captured on 19 September during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been swept from one cache to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organiser of the safari.
An Egyptian security official reported that 30 members of the special forces, on board two helicopters, had launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
"An exchange of shots occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fled," said the official who requested anonymity.
He reported that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the flash unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men in the secret services and special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The previous day, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle carrying the kidnappers, killing in six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture is making headlines and occupying this election campaign.
Good.
But a sector of our cultural life remains forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the amount of misery that is being given to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historic sites that are starving?
What politician dares to remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government devotes three and a half million euros to the restoration of the only Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
Among our American neighbours, it is written in the Constitution of their country that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of the Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, elected officials and government departments, in concert.
In Quebec, at the Fédération des sociétés d'histoire du Québec, at least 40,000 volunteers in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with excavating history, preserving with three under heaps of private archives and preserving archaeological remains.
It is they, often, who are the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when promoters and decision makers launch their bulldozers against our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When is a forum for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Holland bank, as the first European bank in distress as a result of the snowball effect of the US credit market crisis, by partly nationalising it. The three countries are bearing, to the sum of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also owns interest in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed, at the highest level, in this case, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been growing for more than a year is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be taken in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (up to 49%) of the bank's capital in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its holdings, among which, in the first place, the mainly insurance activities it acquired last year from the Dutch organisation ABN Amro.
Last week, the Fortis shares started a staggering fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too large to be allowed to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company's shares fell by 12 percent, to reach its lowest level of 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two thirds of their value.
Taking into account the present value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company's management, is not realistic.
The company's management is aware of the uncertainty, in connection with the adoption of the $700 billion US rescue plan, that it was responsible for the fall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new Managing Director.
The financial agency was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a substantive proposal.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's customer circle and no agency was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also bought leasing companies.
A fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate based on information about his or her drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes which link the use of information on the prescription of medicinal products, in all cases, to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it's like entrusting his hen house to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage medication prescriptions, at the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the capital insured in case of damage depend on the state of health of the client who presents himself, and if they consider that the risk is too great, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent the candidates for a medical examination, and they did not sign an insurance contract with them until they had read the results.
For the past ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains data from pharmacies on the person's medication purchases in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person suffers and what is his or her state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts it in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some at the same time determine a risk coefficient, so there is no longer much to do with the insurer except the paperwork. However, tiny problems may still arise.
One of the disadvantages of this program is that a drug can be used for a variety of purposes. For example, some mixtures may be used against migraine or hot flashes, but may also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others are not.
Companies have developed in the research and analysis of the data and they must ask the patient for authorisation before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their failings in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing the results of laboratory analyses and linking them with data on drug use, and in this way they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of use is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A proposal for a law on the extension of the control circle of the authorities concerning companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his programme, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive agreement of the data subject.
It is also a question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent or not, since if he or she refuses, the insurance does not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus and ultimately, hens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
The global menu of Marseille
The European Union and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trading partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global, problems.
Today, a France-India summit will also be held, focusing on cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is a great emerging democratic power that should be given a wider voice in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support in New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not dwell too much on this issue yesterday at the 9th summit held in Marseilles.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, like the current President of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Diplomacy, Javier Solana, welcomed the Indian Prime Minister, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years they would double trade, which means an increase of a hundred billion euros.
Taking into account that between 2000 and 2007, the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an overly ambitious objective.
In this sense, they have harmonized legally the 26 bilateral conventions with India on civil flights, and in this way air exchanges will also be able to grow in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the situation with India, the EU's largest trading partner, on the one hand, and New Delhi, on the other, which is only ranked ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit devoted its attention to global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a United Nations conference on the subject was raised.
The completion of the Doha trade round has also been called for, although both have much to do with the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains committed to the energy and climate agenda, in particular that it would like to reduce its emissions of toxic materials by at least 20 per cent until 2020.
India also agreed on this, as well as with the fact that a global market would have to be reached at the climate conference next year, and greenhouse gas emissions would have to be reduced by fifty per cent until 2050.
They would also like to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to discuss the financial crisis.
The Indian Head of State is now visiting the French capital, where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that French companies will receive orders worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of Indian atomic reactors.
According to the news agency's information, the agreement would cover 15 years.
