Found Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire missing a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fosset's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying on the Nevada desert, was found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3000 metres, in the area of the Sierra Nevada of Mammanth Lakes, on the California- Nevada border.
Inside the plane, no human remains however.
The sheriff from Madera County, John Anderson, overcame the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it is the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff therefore stated that no human remains were found either on the aircraft or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (Ntsb) reported that a few hours after the wreckage was located, a team of investigators dispatched to the scene identified the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on 3 September 2007, when Fosset decoupled from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal belongings were found by a couple around their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing the name Fosset, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash species and a sweater.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had gained a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
By the sixth attempt, he had become in 2002 the first man to complete the round the world round on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had travelled around the world by plane and without stopover.
Among all these records, also that of flying at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a co-driver.
Glk, the ad you're not expecting.
A 4x4 out of the ordinary of an original and well defined design, with marked lines, wide surfaces and sharp angles.
This is, in summary, Glk, the latest born off road "compact" of the house of the star, with which Mercedes-Benz tried to give a wind of novelty in this sector.
Precisely because of its out-of-standard, unexpected and unconventional content will be the communication that will accompany the launch of the 4x4 Glk, available in the Mercedes-Benz showroom, from next October 17th.
Thus the advertising threshing that will accompany the start of the new car will give rise to an unprecedented communication modality, through a futuristic campaign of 3D displays, used for the first time in Italy by an automotive brand.
A project of maxi displays, articulated in three different phases, which will dominate the heart of Milanese shopping, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication provides for the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision, and thanks to special glasses distributed around Corso Como, it will be possible to see the new 4x4 in almost real dimensions and in three-dimensional format.
Indeed, one will have the impression that by looking at the image, the auto comes out of the poster.
Then, through the use of the innovative Elimina8 technology, the new Glk will be illuminated according to the spots, in all its details, and then recomposed into a single image.
It is obvious that with this advertisement, Mercedes is trying to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of motorist communication.
Will it succeed with this formula to arouse the interest of future acquirers? We will see.
